  "prompt": "Can cheese never be made without rennet?",
  "response": "Cheese can be made without animal rennet. There are several alternatives:\n\n1. Vegetable rennet:\n- Extracted from plants like nettles, thistles, and fig leaves\n- Produces similar curdling effects as animal rennet\n\n2. Microbial rennet:\n- Produced through fermentation of certain fungi and bacteria\n- Commonly used in commercial cheese production\n- Vegetarian and vegan-friendly\n\n3. Acid-based coagulation:\n- Using acids like lemon juice or vinegar\n- Creates soft cheeses like paneer, queso fresco, and ricotta\n- Works by changing milk's protein structure\n\n4. Genetically engineered rennet:\n- Produced using genetically modified microorganisms\n- Creates enzymes identical to traditional animal rennet\n- Does not contain animal products\n\nSome traditional cheeses like cottage cheese, cream cheese, and some fresh cheeses can be made without rennet. However, many hard and aged cheeses traditionally require rennet for proper coagulation and texture.\n\nMany cheese producers now offer vegetarian and vegan cheese options using these alternative coagulation methods.",
